correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003EATP citrate lyase\u003C/strong\u003E, which is activated by insulin to promote lipogenesis. This enzyme catalyses the conversion of citrate to acetyl-CoA in the cytoplasm, providing the essential substrate for fatty acid synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphofructokinase-1\u003C/strong\u003E is a glycolytic enzyme that, while regulated by insulin, is not directly involved in fatty acid synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyruvate dehydrogenase\u003C/strong\u003E converts pyruvate to acetyl-CoA in mitochondria but is not directly activated by insulin for lipogenesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase\u003C/strong\u003E generates NADPH via the pentose phosphate pathway but is not directly activated by insulin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarnitine palmitoyltransferase I\u003C/strong\u003E facilitates fatty acid transport into mitochondria for breakdown and is actually inhibited by insulin\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy activating ATP citrate lyase, insulin increases the cytoplasmic acetyl-CoA pool available for fatty acid synthesis while simultaneously suppressing fatty acid breakdown.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Insulin promotes lipogenesis by activating key enzymes involved in fatty acid synthesis.","ATP citrate lyase converts citrate to acetyl-CoA in the cytoplasm, providing essential substrate for fatty acid synthesis.","Insulin increases ATP citrate lyase activity to promote lipogenesis while suppressing fatty acid breakdown."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. 